comment:
It is a bombshell. And both she & they ACLU have been outed (hard to Bruce this organization is supposed to basically be a civil liberties watchdog, while simultaneously going so far of their way to violate someone's civil liberties...  But It seems to me that the $3.5mil dynamic is they complete opposite. The ACLU wanted her to do the op-ed. She was supposed to give 3.5 mil. She didn't give the money.  *Instead* she agreed to the op-ed. They publicly praised her for donations she never made. Essentially the ACLU paid AH. 

That said, in other sections of those emails, AH wasn't just trying to "mention" her marriage. They also had to reword this but she tried to include:
You had a brilliant solution for the paragraph about not talking about the marriage.

ACLU attempting to moderate AH:
"My concern is this paragraph:

'Then two years ago, after I got a temporary restraining order against my then-husband, I felt the full force of our culture's wrath for women who speak out. The day I left the courtroom and walked into a pack of hundreds of photographers. I didn't have a team of bodyguards-my lawyers used their own bodies to block out space for me to walk to my car. The whole way there, I heard press yelling the same question in one form or another: "Is it true you're making all this up?"'

ACLU:
Could we cut the words "marriage," "divorce," and "restraining order" and say this, below? (If we don't say something like "I became a public figure representing domestic abuse," the rest of the piece doesn't really make sense--it's not clear whether Amber is talking about the abuse she witnessed as a child, what was the pivotal moment that changed things for her, or why she knows about institutions protecting accused"

"While Mr. Depp may believe that everything Ms. Heard says is actually about him, readers blessed with a grasp of English usage and context can readily discern otherwise, especially in a political opinion piece like this one."

comment:
Here is where I am at on this:

Amber H. is a vindictive, conniving, narcissistic bitch.  I know that language may offend so but, it is about the only description that fits.

The fact that the lawyers at the ACLU drafted the Op Ed is not the problem.  Lawyers draft and ghost write things for clients all the time.  As long as the client signs off on it as their statement, that is what it is.

The issue is that it sounds like the ACLU actively solicited for the article as an anti-Trump piece.  When you solicit something like this, you are responsible for it.  That makes them active partners, not just a group providing a service at the direction of a client.

Depp should win this one walking away, assuming the court is fair.  Which is far from a certainty these days.
